Here is an example of how a table of contents (ToC) can be generated automatically in a LaTeX document using the `\tableofcontents` command and the package `tocloft`:

```latex
\documentclass{book}
\usepackage{tocloft}

\begin{document}

\tableofcontents

\addcontentsline{toc}{chapter}{Introduction}
\chapter*{Introduction}

\addcontentsline{toc}{part}{Part I}
\part{Part I Title}

\addcontentsline{toc}{chapter}{Chapter One}
\chapter{Chapter One}

\addcontentsline{toc}{chapter}{Chapter Two}
\chapter{Chapter Two}

\end{document}
```

Let me explain what's happening:

1. `\documentclass{book}` sets the document class to a book-like structure.
2. `\usepackage{tocloft}` loads the `tocloft` package, which provides customization options for the table of contents.
3. `\tableofcontents` generates the table of contents automatically.
4. `\addcontentsline{toc}{chapter/section/part}{heading}` manually adds an entry to the table of contents. The first argument is the name of the ToC file (`toc`), the second argument specifies the level of the entry (e.g., chapter, section, part), and the third argument is the heading text.

When you run this code through LaTeX, it will generate a table of contents that includes the automatically generated entries for the chapters, as well as the manually added entry for the introduction, part title, and any other custom entries you may add.

Note: The `\addcontentsline` command is useful when you need to add custom entries that wouldn't be automatically generated by LaTeX, such as an introduction or a part title that isn't a chapter. For standard chapter and section headings, you don't need to use `\addcontentsline`.

