public class Solution {
    public boolean isPowerOfThree(int n) {
        if (n < 1) return false;
        int max = 1162261467; // 3^19
        return n == 1 || n % 3 == 0 && n % Math.pow(3, Integer.bitCount(Integer.toBinaryString(n)) - 1) == 0 && n <= max;
    }
}
```

Explanation:
This solution works by leveraging the property that the exponent of a power of 3 is the number of 2's in its binary representation minus one. For example, 27 (3^3) is 11111 in binary, which has 4 bits (4 - 1 = 3), and 243 (3^5) is 11111001 in binary, which has 6 bits (6 - 1 = 5).

It first checks if the number is less than 1 and returns false if it is. Then it calculates the maximum power of 3 that is less than the maximum value of an int in Java (2^31 - 1) which is 3^19. It uses this value to restrict the range of the power of 3.

It then checks if the number is 1 (base case) or if the number is divisible by 3, and if the remainder of the number divided by 3 to the power of the number's bit count minus one is zero. If both conditions are met, it returns true, otherwise it returns false.

